At the moment, when the application link is deleted, all the existing mapping for JIRA project to FishEye repository and Crucible project was deleted.

This approach does not really affect small instance as the re-association can can be done in speedy manner. However, for large instance huge number of projects and repositories, administrator need to take a lot of time to re-associate it back. Notes: sometimes the applink need to be re-created because there are changes need to be applied.

Problem is with predicates AFTER, ON and DURING.

JQL:
{code}
status was "Resolved" AFTER "2012-11-08 23:59"
{code}
The results will include all issues that was RESOLVED before "2012-11-08 23:59" e.g. 2012-10-31


{code}
status was "Resolved" ON "2012-11-08"
{code}
The result is the same as the above.


{code}
status was "Resolved" DURING ("2012-11-08","2012-11-20")
{code}
Result is still the same.

So, those 3 optional predicates don't really work and the results shown are similar to using *BEFORE* predicate.

From the [documentation|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/Advanced+Searching#AdvancedSearching-WAS]:
{quote}
Find issues that were resolved by Joe Smith during 2010:
{code}
status WAS "Resolved" BY jsmith DURING ("2010/01/01","2011/01/01")
{code}
{quote}
It is stating that the result would only show issues that were or currently in within that period of time.

See attached build log, in which half the output is caused by hitting this page.

The root cause appears to be a comparator in the MultiSelectCustomFieldSearchRenderer class: {code}    // Used to sort options by value (case insensitive).
    private final static Comparator<Option> OPTION_VALUE_COMPARATOR =
            new Comparator<Option>()
    {
        @Override
        public int compare(Option a, Option b)
        {
            return a.getValue().toLowerCase().compareTo(
                    b.getValue().toLowerCase());
        }
    };{code}

It's not protecting against either the Option or its "value" attribute being null.

